'''Liberty Bartlett''' (born 1810) was a [[United States federal judge|circuit judge]] in Arkansas.
Bartlett was born in 1810 in [[Williamstown, Massachusetts]].<ref name="archive">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/genealogicaland00bartgoog#page/n89|pages=83–84|chapter=Hon. Liberty Bartlett|title=Genealogical and Biographical Sketches of the Bartlett Family in England in America|last=Bartlett|first=Levi|year=1876|publisher=Geo. S. Merrill & Crocker}}</ref> He lived in California for a time, and later moved to Arkansas.<ref name="archive"/> He became a circuit judge of the fifth circuit in [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]] on November 12, 1854.<ref name="archive"/><ref>{{Cite book | last = Goodspeed | first = Weston Arthur | title = The province and the states | publisher = The Western Historical Association | year = 1904 | page = 320 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=BKsvXAap5aMC&pg=PA320}}</ref>
Judge Bartlett attempted to establish a settlement in 1872, at the present site of [[Marche, Arkansas]].<ref name="arkhist">{{Cite web | last = Metrailer | first = Jamie | title = Marche (Pulaski County) | work = The Encyclopedia of Arkansas History & Culture | publisher = The Central Arkansas Library System | date = 12 May 2008 | url = http://www.encyclopediaofarkansas.net/encyclopedia/entry-detail.aspx?entryID=3295# | accessdate = 22 July 2010}}</ref> The settlement, which would have been named Bartlett Springs, did not succeed, and the Little Rock and Fort Smith Railroad ended up acquiring the property and naming it Warren Station.<ref name="arkhist"/> It was later named Marche, and settled by Polish immigrants.
Bartlett was reported to have lived to "extreme old age."<ref>{{Cite book | last = Perry | first = Arthur Latham | title = Williamstown and Williams College | publisher = Norwood Press | year = 1899 | page = 534 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Y3MWAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA534}}</ref>
